we found that actually they belong to the genus 
<taxonomicName authority="Macquart. Melander (1928)" authorityName="Macquart. Melander" authorityYear="1928" box="[523,972,1311,1336]" class="Insecta" family="Hybotidae" genus="Platypalpus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="36" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[523,657,1312,1336]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="36">Platypalpus</emphasis>
Macquart. 
<bibRefCitation author="Melander" box="[784,972,1311,1335]" pageId="1" pageNumber="36" refString="Melander, A. L. (1928) Diptera, Fam. Empididae. In: Wytsman, P. (Ed.), Genera Insectorum Fasc. 185. Louis Desmet- Verteneuil, Bruxelles, 434 pp." type="book" year="1928">
Melander (
<number box="[905,963,1311,1335]" pageId="1" pageNumber="36" value="1928.0">1928</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
did not provide any comparative analysis of 
<taxonomicName box="[182,372,1348,1372]" class="Insecta" family="Hybotidae" genus="Charadrodromia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="36" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[182,372,1348,1372]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="36">Charadrodromia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
but his key to the genera and subgenera of the 
<taxonomicName box="[906,1088,1348,1372]" class="Insecta" family="Hybotidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="36" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Tachydromiinae">Tachydromiinae</taxonomicName>
(l.c.: 
<number box="[1155,1198,1348,1372]" pageId="1" pageNumber="36" value="270.0">270</number>
) indicates diagnostic features that Melander thought to be crucial to erect a separate genus: first basal cell equal to or longer than the second, anal cell not formed; face narrower than frons; two pairs each of ocellar and vertical bristles; arista apical; humeri constricted; legs not evidently bristly; cheeks linear; notum with coarse hairs but no strong anterior dorsocentrals.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,1276,1948]" pageId="1" pageNumber="36">
It is evident that none of the characters applied by Melander could be used to distinguish 
<taxonomicName box="[1247,1436,1528,1552]" class="Insecta" family="Hybotidae" genus="Charadrodromia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="36" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1247,1436,1528,1552]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="36">Charadrodromia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from 
<taxonomicName box="[212,346,1564,1588]" class="Insecta" family="Hybotidae" genus="Platypalpus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="36" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[212,346,1564,1588]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="36">Platypalpus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Relative lengths of cells br and bm of the wing (= first and second basal cells) are quite variable in 
<taxonomicName box="[187,321,1600,1624]" class="Insecta" family="Hybotidae" genus="Platypalpus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="36" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[187,321,1600,1624]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="36">Platypalpus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
including North American species (e.g., Chillcott 
<number box="[939,999,1599,1623]" pageId="1" pageNumber="36" value="1962.0">1962</number>
: 
<number box="[1018,1062,1599,1623]" pageId="1" pageNumber="36" value="117.0">117</number>
, figs. 
<number box="[1144,1203,1599,1623]" pageId="1" pageNumber="36" value="9.0" valueMax="10.0" valueMin="8.0">8–10</number>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Chvala" box="[1222,1376,1599,1623]" pageId="1" pageNumber="36" refString="Chvala, M. (1975) The Tachydromiinae (Dipt. Empididae) of Fennoscandia and Denmark. Fauna Entomologica Scandinavica, 3, 1 - 336." type="journal article" year="1975">
Chvála 
<number box="[1316,1376,1599,1623]" pageId="1" pageNumber="36" value="1975.0">1975</number>
</bibRefCitation>
: figs 
<number box="[151,254,1636,1660]" pageId="1" pageNumber="36" value="710.5" valueMax="747.0" valueMin="674.0">674–747</number>
). In 
<taxonomicName box="[307,441,1636,1660]" class="Insecta" family="Hybotidae" genus="Platypalpus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="36" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[307,441,1636,1660]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="36">Platypalpus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
the anal cell (or cell cu 
<emphasis box="[716,730,1637,1660]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="36">p</emphasis>
) is usually closed (anal vein distinct basally) but rarely (e.g., some species of the 
<taxonomicName box="[405,549,1672,1696]" class="Insecta" family="Hybotidae" genus="Platypalpus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="36" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hackmani">
<emphasis box="[405,549,1672,1696]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="36">P. hackmani</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group) it is not quite formed (anal vein wanting or evanescent basally). Furthermore, the anal vein is distinct in 
<taxonomicName box="[600,722,1708,1732]" class="Insecta" family="Hybotidae" genus="Platypalpus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="36" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="arnaudi">
<emphasis box="[600,722,1708,1732]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="36">C. arnaudi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(cf. 
<figureCitation box="[774,841,1708,1732]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 5" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1818,1841]" captionTargetBox="[236,1360,687,1785]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[226,1361,682,1797]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 5. Platypalpus arnaudi (Melander), male. 1. habitus, lateral view. 2. wing, dorsal view. 3. right epandrial lamella, lateral view. 4. epandrium with cerci and hypoproct, dorsal view. 5. left epandrial lamella and left cercus, lateral view." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/282719/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="36">
Fig. 
<number box="[826,841,1708,1732]" pageId="1" pageNumber="36" value="2.0">2</number>
</figureCitation>
) and evanescent in other species of 
<taxonomicName box="[1247,1436,1708,1732]" class="Insecta" family="Hybotidae" genus="Charadrodromia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="36" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1247,1436,1708,1732]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="36">Charadrodromia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[159,238,1743,1767]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1249,1272]" captionTargetBox="[272,1314,465,1228]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[255,1332,445,1228]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 6. Platypalpus microphona (Melander), habitus, female (paralectotype), lateral view." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/282720/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="36">Figs. 6</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[250,266,1743,1767]" captionStart="FIGURES 7 – 11" captionStartId="6.[151,264,1863,1886]" captionTargetBox="[155,1427,477,1829]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[265,1321,1092,1829]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 7 – 11. Platypalpus syletor (Melander). 7. apical part of right epandrial lamella, ventral view. 8. right epandrial lamella, lateral view. 9. cerci and epandrium, dorsal view. 10. left epandrial lamella, lateral view. 11. habitus, female (holotype), lateral view." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/282721/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="36">7</figureCitation>
). Finally, the length of ocellar bristles varies in 
<taxonomicName box="[798,932,1744,1768]" class="Insecta" family="Hybotidae" genus="Platypalpus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="36" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[798,932,1744,1768]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="36">Platypalpus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and even in 
<taxonomicName box="[1074,1263,1744,1768]" class="Insecta" family="Hybotidae" genus="Charadrodromia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="36" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1074,1263,1744,1768]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="36">Charadrodromia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Consequently, 
<taxonomicName box="[151,340,1780,1804]" class="Insecta" family="Hybotidae" genus="Charadrodromia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="36" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[151,340,1780,1804]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="36">Charadrodromia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is viewed here as a junior synonym of 
<taxonomicName box="[779,913,1780,1804]" class="Insecta" family="Hybotidae" genus="Platypalpus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="36" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[779,913,1780,1804]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="36">Platypalpus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,1276,1948]" pageId="1" pageNumber="36">
The genus 
<taxonomicName box="[328,489,1816,1840]" class="Insecta" family="Hybotidae" genus="Chersodromia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="36" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[328,489,1816,1840]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="36">Chersodromia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from which 
<taxonomicName box="[641,831,1816,1840]" class="Insecta" family="Hybotidae" genus="Charadrodromia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="36" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[641,831,1816,1840]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="36">Charadrodromia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was distinguished in Melander’s key belongs to the tribe 
<taxonomicName box="[209,315,1852,1876]" class="Insecta" family="Hybotidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="36" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Drapetini">Drapetini</taxonomicName>
that is diagnosed by several distinctive apomorphies (
<bibRefCitation author="Sinclair" box="[916,1260,1852,1876]" pageId="1" pageNumber="36" refString="Sinclair, B. J. &amp; Cumming, J. M. (2006) The morphology, higher-level phylogeny and classification of the Empidoidea (Diptera). Zootaxa, 1180, 1 - 172." type="journal article" year="2006">
Sinclair &amp; Cumming 
<number box="[1158,1218,1852,1876]" pageId="1" pageNumber="36" value="2006.0">2006</number>
: 
<number box="[1228,1260,1852,1876]" pageId="1" pageNumber="36" value="79.0">79</number>
</bibRefCitation>
). Unfortunately Melander's (
<number box="[291,349,1887,1911]" pageId="1" pageNumber="36" value="1928.0">1928</number>
) misleading key (p. 
<number box="[586,631,1887,1911]" pageId="1" pageNumber="36" value="270.0">270</number>
, couplets 
<number box="[746,760,1887,1911]" pageId="1" pageNumber="36" value="6.0">6</number>
and 
<number box="[818,833,1887,1911]" pageId="1" pageNumber="36" value="7.0">7</number>
) to the genera and subgenera of the 
<taxonomicName box="[1254,1435,1887,1911]" class="Insecta" family="Hybotidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="36" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Tachydromiinae">Tachydromiinae</taxonomicName>
was applied in the Manual of Nearctic 
<taxonomicName authority="Steyskal &amp; Knutson 1981" authorityName="Steyskal &amp; Knutson" authorityYear="1981" box="[585,987,1924,1948]" kingdom="Plantae" order="Diptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="36" rank="order">
Diptera (
<bibRefCitation author="Steyskal" box="[684,978,1924,1948]" pageId="1" pageNumber="36" refString="Steyskal, G. C. &amp; Knutson, L. V. (1981) Empididae [Chapter] 47. In McAlpine, J. F., Peterson, B. V., Shewell, G. E., Teskey, H. J., Vockeroth, J. R. &amp; Wood, D. M. (Coords.), Manual of Nearctic Diptera, Volume 1. Agriculture Canada Monograph, 27, 607 - 624." type="journal article" year="1981">
Steyskal &amp; Knutson 
<number box="[918,978,1924,1948]" pageId="1" pageNumber="36" value="1981.0">1981</number>
</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
